<p>Firestore is a NoSQL  (“non-relational” or “Not only SQL”), document-oriented database.</p>

<p>There are 4 different types of NoSQL databases:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Wide column like Cassandra</li>
  <li>Document like MongoDB or Firestore…</li>
  <li>Key–value like Redis</li>
  <li>Graph like InfiniteGraph</li>
</ul>

<p>Firestore can be categorized in the type “Document” with databases like MongoDB, Apache CouchDB… So firestore, like other document-oriented databases, encapsulate and encode data (or information) in documents. Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON. Documents are addressed in the database via a unique key that represents that document.</p>
